 	   	  		<h2 class="pagetitle">Archive for April, 2005</h2>
 	  

				<div class="post-124 post type-post status-publish format-standard category-apartheid category-economics category-politics h-entry hentry h-as-article">
				<h3 id="post-124"><a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2005/04/27/open-h1b-gates/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Open the H1B Gates"><span class='p-name'>Open the H1B Gates</span></a></h3>
				<small>Wednesday, April 27th, 2005</small>

				<div class="entry">
					<div class='e-content'><p>Credit (<a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2004/07/11/bill-gates-for-broken-windows/">and</a> <a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2005/01/10/infoanarchy-drm-celestial-jukebox/">blame</a>) where due: Kudos to Bill Gates for clearly saying that <a href="http://news.com.com/Gates+wants+to+scrap+H-1B+visas/2100-1022_3-5687039.html">H-1B caps should be scrapped</a>. Yes, and so should all other restrictions on travel and work across borders.</p>
<p>Gates and others have warned that American companies need foreign engineering talent to stay competitive. I believe that is the case for most businesses, but if there was an exception it should be Microsoft. There should be no advantage to being <a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2005/04/20/really-offshoring/">close to the customer</a> in developing shrink-wrap software, as the customer is everywhere. Why should a shrink-wrap developer care about where engineering talent is located? Why not, e.g., move all Microsoft Office development to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyderabad%2C_India#Economy">Hyderabad</a>? Inertia I suppose. It may be hard to relocate Office development anywhere outside the Seattle area. Surely any wholly new shrink-wrap development teams ought to be located outside the U.S, barring H-1B liberalization.</p>
<p><small><em><a href="http://techdirt.com/articles/20050427/1435225_F.shtml">Via Techdirt.</a></em></small></p>
</div>				</div>

